viral DNA","The viral genome without any protein coating","Surface glycoproteins that bind to host cells"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eprotein shell enclosing viral genetic material\u003C/strong\u003E correctly describes the nucleocapsid, which is composed of multiple copies of capsid proteins arranged in a specific geometric pattern around the viral genome. This structure provides protection for the viral genetic material and helps mediate viral entry into host cells.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EA lipid envelope surrounding viral proteins\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the viral envelope, which is present in some but not all viruses and is distinct from the nucleocapsid\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe viral genome without any protein coating\u003C/strong\u003E - The viral genome alone without protein coating would be vulnerable to degradation\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurface glycoproteins that bind to host cells\u003C/strong\u003E - These are viral attachment proteins that facilitate entry into host cells but are not part of the nucleocapsid\u003C/li\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThe enzyme complex that replicates viral DNA\u003C/strong\u003E - This refers to viral polymerases and other replication machinery, not the structural nucleocapsid\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe nucleocapsid is essential for viral survival and infectivity, providing both structural stability and functional roles in the viral life cycle.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A nucleocapsid is the complete protein shell (capsid) that surrounds the viral genome (nucleic acid).","Nucleocapsids can have different geometric arrangements including icosahedral and helical structures.","The nucleocapsid protects the viral genome and assists in cell entry and viral assembly."],"references":["Murray PR, Rosenthal KS, Pfaller MA. Medical Microbiology. 8th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61156"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18550"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61156","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61156"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T12:57:33+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T12:58:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11282"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75638"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4936","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4936"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immune System","synonyms":[],"description":null,"